<BR><h2><A NAME="files">
<IMG SRC="/pub/Graphics/Icons/doc1_icon.gif" ALT=""></A>
Files in this Archive</h2>

<DL>
<DT><a href="clipper_foia.note"><B>clipper_foia.note</B></a>
<DD>CUD article from April 1994 discussing Gilmore's FOIA
    suit against the NSA for clipper key database.
<DT><a href="clipper_foia.update"><B>clipper_foia.update</B></a>
<DD>Lee Tien's May 1994 update describing what
    information has been attained through the FOIA suit.
<DT><a href="clipper_foia_appeal.letters"><B>clipper_foia_appeal.letters</B></a>
<DD>John Gilmore's May 1994 post describing how
    his case is going and includes two letter from
    Tien which show how hard it is to get through
    the red tape the gov't wraps you with in
    order to paralyze your progress.
<DT><a href="clipper_nist.defense"><B>clipper_nist.defense</B></a>
<DD>1994 statement by NIST regarding key escrow and
    how it is intended to be &quot;voluntary&quot;. NIST maintains the same thing in
    1995, even though FOIA-obtained documents *prove* this is a lie!
<DT><a href="epic_clipper_foia_1095.announce"><B>epic_clipper_foia_1095.announce</B></a>
<DD>EPIC press relase regaring renewed
    efforts to obtain information from NSA about Clipper and Administration 
    crypto policy. Refers to a brief EPIC submitted in support of CPSR's
    FOIA lawsuit against NSA (see epic_clipper_foia_1095.brief below).
<DT><a href="epic_clipper_foia_1095.brief"><B>epic_clipper_foia_1095.brief</B></a>
<DD>EPIC amicus brief filed in support of CPSR's
    lawsuit against the NSA. Argues forcefully that NSA is prevaricating,
    that Clipper was classified for law enforcement convenience and political
    value, rather than &quot;national security&quot;.
<DT><a href="epic_clipper_secrets.announce"><B>epic_clipper_secrets.announce</B></a>
<DD>EPIC press release regarding recently
    obtained FBI documents, from a related FOIA case, proving that the 
    Clinton administration has been lying about its intentions to not 
    make Clipper or other &quot;key escrow&quot; schemes mandatory or to outlaw 
    non-&quot;escrowed&quot; encryption. Aug. 1995.
</DL>

